===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|lernen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|leornian||lang=ang|to acquire knowledge}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|liznaną|lang=gem-pro}}. Compare {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|lernen|lang=de}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|learns|learning|'''[[learned]]''' or '''[[learnt]]''' ''(chiefly UK)''}}

# To [[acquire]], or attempt to acquire [[knowledge]] or an ability to do something.
# To [[attend]] a course or other [[educational]] activity.
#* '''1719''', [[w:Daniel Defoe|Daniel Defoe]], ''[[w:Robinson Crusoe|Robinson Crusoe]]''
#*: ''For, as he took delight to introduce me, I took delight to '''learn.'''''
# To gain knowledge from a bad [[experience]].
#: '''''learn''' from one's mistakes''
# To [[improve]], maybe used in an order.
#: '''''Learn''' how to do it better!''
# To be studying.
# To come to [[know]]; to become [[inform]]ed of; to [[find out]].
#: ''He just '''learned''' that he will be sacked.''
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} To communicate knowledge to; to teach.
#* Shakespeare
#*: Hast thou not '''learned''' me how / To make perfumes?

